		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Are pure primary colors ever useful in a color ramp?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />An HDTV receiving a 1080i signal, such as broadcast or cable TV, is likely to lag to deinterlace it. It may lag even when receiving a progressive signal in order to run various enhancement filters on the image, but better TVs have a &quot;game mode&quot; option to turn enhancement down to minimum.<br /><br />Among LCDs, IPS is more consistent than TN at different viewing angles. This is why smartphones and tablet computers are more likely to use IPS, as a portrait-oriented tablet will have the user's two eyes at significantly different viewing angles.<br /><br />The problem with using old TVs with old consoles is twofold. For one thing, old TVs are less likely to fit in a cramped apartment. For another, old TVs wear out. My 27&quot; Magnavox died, and now I'm back on a 13&quot; Panasonic.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


